
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `linux32` baraye ejra kardan yek barname 32-biti dar yek system 64-biti estefade mishavad. In be karbar ijaze mide barname haye ghadeemi ro ke faghat baraye architecture 32-bit neveshte shode and, ejra kone.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `linux32 bash`  --> 💻 Terminal bash ra dar mode 32-bit baz mikonad.
    🔹 `linux32 ./my_program` --> 🚀 Barname "my_program" ra dar mode 32-bit ejra mikonad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ linux32 uname -m

    🔹 Namayesh memari system dar mode 32-bit (bayad i686 ya chizi shabihe oon neshun bede).

    $ linux32 file /bin/ls

    🔹 Check mikonad ke aya /bin/ls yek file 32-biti hast ya na. Agar 32-biti bashad, etelaati dar in mored neshun mide.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ linux32 bash
    $ uname -m
    i686

    🔹 In mesal terminal bash ra dar mode 32-bit baz mikonad va ba estefade az `uname -m`, memari system ra check mikonad. Agar `i686` neshun dade shavad, yani shoma dar hale ejra dar mode 32-bit hastid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `linux32` command is used to execute a 32-bit program on a 64-bit system.  It allows users to run older applications that were designed only for a 32-bit architecture.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `linux32 bash`  --> 💻 Opens a bash terminal in 32-bit mode.
    🔹 `linux32 ./my_program` --> 🚀 Executes the program "my_program" in 32-bit mode.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ linux32 uname -m

    🔹 Shows the system architecture in 32-bit mode (should display i686 or similar).

    $ linux32 file /bin/ls

    🔹 Checks if /bin/ls is a 32-bit file. If it is, information about it is displayed.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ linux32 bash
    $ uname -m
    i686

    🔹 This example opens a bash terminal in 32-bit mode and then uses `uname -m` to check the system architecture. If `i686` is displayed, it means you are running in 32-bit mode.
